Inheritance is an OOP concept where one class acquires the properties (variables) and behaviors (methods) of another class.

Inheritance exists to solve three major problems:
- Code Reusability : Avoid writing the same code again and again.
- Extensibility : Add new behavior without modifying existing code.
- Polymorphism Support : Parent reference can point to child objects.

Terminology:
| Parent class | Superclass / Base class               |
| Child class  | Subclass / Derived class              |
| `extends`    | Keyword used to inherit               |

Example:
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        super.sound();  // calls Animal's method
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
Dog d = new Dog();
d.sound();
